      <!-- ============================ FAQ ============================ -->
      <section id="faq" class="bg-slate-50 border-y border-slate-200">
        <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-14">
          <h2 class="text-3xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-slate-900 text-center">
            Frequently asked questions
          </h2>
          <p class="mt-3 text-center text-slate-600">
            Common questions about heat pump sizing, heating vs. cooling loads, and cold-climate units.
          </p>

          <div class="mt-8 space-y-3">
            <details class="group rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5">
              <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer font-semibold text-slate-900">
                What size heat pump do I need?
                <svg
                  class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-indigo-600 transition-transform group-open:rotate-45"
                  fill="none"
                  stroke="currentColor"
                  stroke-width="2"
                  viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                >
                  <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4v16m8-8H4"></path>
                </svg>
              </summary>
              <p class="mt-3 text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">
                Size to the larger of your heating and cooling loads, but in practice most US homes size the
                heat pump to the <strong>cooling load</strong> (≈20 BTU/sq ft adjusted for climate, sun,
                insulation) so it dehumidifies properly, then cover any winter shortfall with backup heat or
                a cold-climate model. A 1,800 sq ft mixed-climate home is typically 3 tons.
              </p>
            </details>

            <details class="group rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5">
              <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer font-semibold text-slate-900">
                Are heat pumps sized differently from air conditioners?
                <svg
                  class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-indigo-600 transition-transform group-open:rotate-45"
                  fill="none"
                  stroke="currentColor"
                  stroke-width="2"
                  viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                >
                  <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4v16m8-8H4"></path>
                </svg>
              </summary>
              <p class="mt-3 text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">
                The cooling side is sized just like an AC. The difference is you must <strong>also</strong>
                check the heating load, which in cold climates is much larger — that's why heat pump sizing
                adds a balance-point check.
              </p>
            </details>

            <details class="group rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5">
              <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer font-semibold text-slate-900">
                What is a heat pump's balance point?
                <svg
                  class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-indigo-600 transition-transform group-open:rotate-45"
                  fill="none"
                  stroke="currentColor"
                  stroke-width="2"
                  viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                >
                  <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4v16m8-8H4"></path>
                </svg>
              </summary>
              <p class="mt-3 text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">
                The outdoor temperature where the heat pump's output exactly equals the home's heat loss.
                Above it the heat pump handles everything; below it you need supplemental/backup heat.
                Cold-climate (inverter) heat pumps push the balance point much lower.
              </p>
            </details>

            <details class="group rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5">
              <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer font-semibold text-slate-900">
                Do I need a cold-climate heat pump?
                <svg
                  class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-indigo-600 transition-transform group-open:rotate-45"
                  fill="none"
                  stroke="currentColor"
                  stroke-width="2"
                  viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                >
                  <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4v16m8-8H4"></path>
                </svg>
              </summary>
              <p class="mt-3 text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">
                If your heating load is far above your cooling load (Zone 5+), yes — ENERGY STAR cold-climate
                models keep <strong>≥70% of rated capacity at 5°F</strong> and have <strong>HSPF2 ≥ 8.5</strong>,
                so they heat efficiently without leaning on resistance backup.
              </p>
            </details>

            <details class="group rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5">
              <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer font-semibold text-slate-900">
                Should I oversize a heat pump for cold winters?
                <svg
                  class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-indigo-600 transition-transform group-open:rotate-45"
                  fill="none"
                  stroke="currentColor"
                  stroke-width="2"
                  viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                >
                  <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4v16m8-8H4"></path>
                </svg>
              </summary>
              <p class="mt-3 text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">
                Not by oversizing the cooling capacity — that causes short-cycling and poor summer humidity
                control. Instead pick a cold-climate unit or add staged backup heat. Right-size to cooling,
                solve heating separately.
              </p>
            </details>

            <details class="group rounded-xl border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5">
              <summary class="flex items-center justify-between cursor-pointer font-semibold text-slate-900">
                How accurate is this vs. a Manual J?
                <svg
                  class="h-5 w-5 shrink-0 text-indigo-600 transition-transform group-open:rotate-45"
                  fill="none"
                  stroke="currentColor"
                  stroke-width="2"
                  viewBox="0 0 24 24"
                >
                  <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" d="M12 4v16m8-8H4"></path>
                </svg>
              </summary>
              <p class="mt-3 text-slate-600 text-sm leading-relaxed">
                It's a solid planning estimate using climate-zone BTU-per-sq-ft rules. A full
                <strong>ACCA Manual J</strong> accounts for windows, orientation, infiltration, and duct
                losses and is required for permits and warranties. Use this to plan, a Manual J to install.
              </p>
            </details>
          </div>
        </div>
      </section>

